  • Diabetes is a chronic condition resulting in high blood sugar levels due to insufficient insulin production or utilization.
  • Types: Type 1 (immune-mediated), Type 2 (lifestyle-related), and gestational diabetes (during pregnancy).
  • Complications include cardiovascular disease, nerve damage, kidney damage, eye damage, and foot damage.
  • Global prevalence is rising, with an estimated 463 million adults affected in 2019.
  • Management involves medication, diet, exercise, monitoring blood sugar levels, and education for prevention of complications.
); } export default BetterList;
